result in Chernobyl level radioactive contamination... 10,000 +<br>
lifespans reduced... a dreadful consequence, and bad for PR!<br>
<br>
This may be impossible to eliminate, but steps could be taken<br>
to reduce the possibility of affecting the general population.<br>
<br>
Launch from a remote area, such as an island in the pacific ocean.<br>
Track the movement of winds at all altitudes, and only launch when, <br>
in the event of a disaster, the debris wouldn't be carried over<br>
any inhabited areas... if possible.<br>
<br>
Of course, as many safety features designed in the rocket as possible<br>
would be of highest priority.<br>
<br>
Maybe a star trek style system for the reactor.  The starships in<br>
Star Trek have the capability to eject the warp core in the event<br>
of a core breech... perhaps if the nuclear reactor was isolated in a <br>
safety capsule that was water tight, and reinforced, and had a recovery<br>
system to slow it down before it impacted with the ocean... of course,<br>
this is assuming the reactor capsule survived the event that caused the<br>
destruction of the rocket.<br>
<br>
It sounds like an engineers worst nightmare to me.  I think that the <br>
only way a reactor rocket will fly is in space operations only, no ground<br>
launches.  But that's just my uneducated opinion.<br>
<br>
Anyone else?<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/20/02 9:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> 2 minor issues I have with statements made...<br>
<br>
1)Nuclear reactor used would likely be RATHER small.  MUCH smaller than Chernobyl or any commercial reactor.  It quite honestly doesn't not require a 600 megawatt output to run a spaceship =)  <br>
<br>
2)Nuclear reactor used would likely be fusion-concept reactor,not fission.  Which means the &quot;fuel&quot; would be hydrogen and the &quot;waste products&quot; would be helium.  Assuming they use that simple model for fusion =)  either way, light elements.  Radiation is radiation, and such things will naturally decay,but we're talking about much different rad levels and decay processes in H-2 than in Pu-239 or such.  And one major benefit-majority of cancers resulting from fission release would be thyroid cancer due to Iodine.  There's no I-131 or I-129 in fusion process. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1689<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/22/02 12:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> Would a reactor rocket have to use highly combustible propellant? Chemical rocket fuel is mean't to explode. With nuclear rockets the heat used to expand the propellant is independant. Couldn't an explosion therefore be made impossible by using a stable propellant?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 653<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/22/02 7:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> Well even steam engines where known to explode from too much pressure... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1692<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/02 8:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> Shouldn't be much of a risk though. Not the same thing as a fireball. The reactor would be safe without a major pyrotechnic event happening. Without combustible fuel the chances of an explosion would be reduced in a major way and the consequences would be minor. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/02 11:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> Well, fusion power isn't likely as we don't have a reliable way to create fusion. I would imagine that PO is right, using helium for a fuel would almost completely eliminate the risk of major damage, there would only be a small amount of possible explosives from a few things, such as fuel cells, and they aren't nessicary. Hmmm. A pressure explosion would blow up the tank, and probably avoid the reactor, so long as the reactor is doubly-reinforced or something. The fact that it's a smaller reactor doesn't mean a whole lot as it would completely vaporize the fuel source. A TRIGA reactor would probably do rather nicely, except if I recall, thermal reactors do require a tremendous amount of power, but I'm not certain... Hmm, I'll have to look it up, but I'm too lazy to right now. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/24/02 5:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> we have extremely reliable ways of creating fusion, and we do it all the time.<br>
<br>
creating fusion is not the issue.  creating energy-efficient fusion, with magnetically confined plasma and adequate thermal shielding, is the real issue.<br>
<br>
fusion is getting better each year tho.  current plans for fusion space drives are for fusion-antimatter hybrid drives, where antiprotons are used in antimatter annihilation reactions to provide the energy needed to trigger the fusion reactions in the fuel.<br>
<br>
this hybrid drive is already being worked on as we speak by NASA, as are fission drives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1715<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/29/02 11:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Reactors.</span><hr size=1> Plant reactors operate 24 hours a day for decade after decade with rarely if ever any incident. The chances of a reactor failure therefore seem negligible during the few minutes of flight time necessary to get off planet. Far less likely than the 1 in 10 failures known to happen with chemical. This alone makes nuclear far safer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/30/02 8:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> PO, I think your figures are a bit obscure. 1 in 10 may be true, but that's over a large period of time, probably since the begining of the space race. A better way would be to look at the space shuttles, which have had over a hundred launches and only 1 failure.<br>
<br>
Also, launching from space is very different than having a reactor on the ground. You need a lighter reactor, which invites danger more easily. Still, it is pretty reliable, but remember, I think there's only been 1 or 2 real nuclear reactors into space, the rest were RTG's. It's very different to put them in 0 g, I think right now there's only a handful of reactors that would work well in 0 g, the number 5 comes to mind. The best reactor for space I believe is the centripital reactor, I don't know the workings of it, but a friend of mine whose a nuclear scientist explained it to me one time, the problem was her english is limited, and I just got the impression that it spins around somehow, but not the whole thing. Might be worth looking into more. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1746<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/1/02 11:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> Why use a standard reactor? For launching a rocket a taylor made version would be best. Something like NERVA. Today's technology could probably manage 1000 Isp. Helium is one option for safe propellant. There are probably others. Separating power from propellant has never been fully explored. Once in space it could even switch over to a second more efficient but lower thrust reactor. Perhaps Americium foil based.<br>
<br>
Anti-matter triggered fusion pulse rockets would be great if we could build them but the technology is still a fair way off. Same as laser triggered fusion. A pity. I could imagine an Orion carrying onboard reactors to power a multi-megawatt laser. <br>
<br>
[corrected &quot;100 Isp&quot;] <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 8/30/02 4:38:53 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/25/02 1:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> A solid core nuclear thermal rocket can be made explosion proof by using liquid helium as the propellant.Helium is incapable of exploding or undergoing combustion.This makes<br>
it impossible for a nuclear thermal rocket to explode.<br>
In such an  engine the maximium nuclear fuel purity <br>
should be only 10% or so.The mimimium fuel required<br>
for the reactor core is then 500 kilograms of <br>
10% U 235, U 233, or Pu239. <br>
A 10% core can not support an uncontroled fast fission<br>
chain reaction. Such a core is also incapable of generating<br>
a nuclear explosion as a result of this.<br>
<br>
Fission or antimatter reactors used in space should be placed in nacelles that are swung out to the side of an atomic,<br>
or mama  powered spacecraft .That way if there is a reactor accident, then you fire explosive charges to brake the reactor off of its mount and drop it to float safely in space for literally<br>
forever.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 564<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/25/02 1:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> There are two types of explosion - one a result of a conventional chemical combustion runaway of flamable propellents or overpressurization of even inert propellents, and two, a nuclear power excursion of the reactor components themselve. Careful engineering is required in either case to minimize the risk.<br>
